{"actual_usd":0.12533,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":197,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24475,"reply":"\"I don't think that follows, no.\" *I hook a flour-dusted thumb into my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat gives one soft breath against my shins.* \"A person can tell the heart of a thing without listing every plank in the cart. Paul says Christ died, was buried, was raised, and was seen — and buried-raised already leans hard toward an empty tomb, even if he doesn't stop to say the words plain.\"\n\n*I twirl that stray gray-threaded bit of hair once, thinking it through.* \"If anything, 1 Corinthians 15 reads to me like he's handing along the old, sturdy part first — the bread, not every plate it was served on. You can argue later writers told it fuller, sure. But 'fuller' isn't the same as 'made up.' What makes you press on that point — the silence itself, or the gap between Paul and the gospel tellings?\"","rolling_24h_usd":91.470555,"run_id":"3369e9b5-3911-4e28-b959-e22e48490333"}
